            reviewDate: 'June 23, 2024',
            semester: 'spring 2024',
            review: "A little about me: I graduated with a bachelor's degree in CS last summer and got a SWE job midway through this course. This was my first course in the OMSCS program, and I got an A with a 91%. I had 99% before the last two projects, for which I did the minimum required to get an A.\nIt's a survey course covering eight different security topics, split into 4 easier ones (with 10 days to complete each) and 4 more challenging ones (with 14 days to complete each). For the easier topics, I spent about 10 hours each, while the challenging ones took me between 15 to 30 hours. If you get stuck, though, there's little to almost no help available, perhaps the discussion board can help, but that's about it (For this reason, I recommend starting a little late so you can get more help). Don't get me wrong, the course isn't hard, but it does feel like they want you to learn the hard way. Clearer instructions could easily reduce a 10 hour project to 3 hours.\nOverall, I think it's a good course if you haven't taken a security course before or if you're interested in security topics. However, I wouldn't recommend taking it just because it's \"easy,\" as getting stuck can be a real headache.\nPro:\n\nYou know your score instantly for every project\nEight projects, no lectures, no quizzes or exams, no participation requirements, and no group work\nRelatively low time commitment\n\nCon:\n\nUnclear instructions turn a 3-hour project into a 10-hour one\nThere's too much emphasis on catching cheaters rather than encouraging learning. For example, students are only allowed to communicate through the discussion board or Slack. Forming your own study groups is not allowed, and you can't contact other students privately for help\nI sometimes feel like I'm solving puzzles rather than taking a graduate level course.\n",
